# TypeScript Rules

## Strictness

- `tsconfig.json` runs in strict mode (`strict: true`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true`).
- No `any`. Use `unknown` and narrow.
- No non-null assertions (`!`) on values that crossed an API or DB boundary — validate with zod first.

## Validation at boundaries

```ts
// BAD
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const body = await req.json();
  await imageService.create(body);  // unchecked input
}

// GOOD
const CreateImageSchema = z.object({
  prompt: z.string().min(1).max(2000),
  tags: z.array(z.string()).max(20).default([]),
  storageKey: z.string().min(1),
});

export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const parsed = CreateImageSchema.safeParse(await req.json());
  if (!parsed.success) return Response.json({ error: parsed.error }, { status: 400 });
  await imageService.create(parsed.data);
}
```

## Error handling

```ts
// BAD
try { await thing(); } catch {}

// GOOD
try {
  await thing();
} catch (err) {
  errors.capture(err, { op: "thing", imageId });
  throw new ServiceError("thing_failed", { cause: err });
}
```

Use the `errors` adapter from `lib/observability/errors.ts` — never call Sentry directly.

## Imports

- Absolute imports rooted at `@/*` (configured in `tsconfig.json`).
- No deep imports across layers — services import from repos, not the other way around.
